# Universal Code Constitution

## Table of Contents & Resources
- [Core Concepts](#core-concepts)
- [Examples: Guard Clauses](resources/examples-guard-clauses.md)
- [Reference: Forbidden Patterns](resources/reference-forbidden-patterns.md)

## Core Concepts

### Guard Clauses (Tiger-Style)
At function start, early returns for invalid inputs. Single success path at the end.
- Max 3 nesting levels
- Minimum 2 guards per significant function
- Fast-fail for invalid state

### Pure Functions
Functions should have no side effects where possible.
- Same input → same output
- No hidden state mutation
- Explicit dependencies via parameters

### Linear Code (Tiger-Style)
One successful path through the function. Guard clauses handle early exits; the success path stays linear.

- Guard clauses are the only early returns
- Converge all success flow to a single return/commit point
- Ternary is for value selection only, never control flow or side effects
- Prefer straight-line flow over if/else ladders; refactor to guard clauses + linear core
- **Performance**: fewer branches reduces overhead, improves branch prediction on hot paths, and makes tuning reliable

### Single Responsibility
Each function does one thing well.
- Max 60 lines per function (smell threshold at 40; investigate if exceeding)
- Complexity ≤5 (cyclomatic)
- Max 500 lines per module/file

### Descriptive Names
Names should be self-documenting.
- No abbreviations (use `request` not `req`, `configuration` not `cfg`)
- No single-letter variables except loop indices
- Include units where applicable (`timeout_seconds`, `size_bytes`)

### Import Organization
Group imports consistently:
1. Standard library / built-in
2. Third-party packages
3. First-party / project code

No wildcards; keep imports at file top.

### Forbidden Patterns

| Pattern | Why Forbidden |
|---------|---------------|
| Bare except / catch-all | Swallows errors, hides bugs |
| Global mutable state | Hidden dependencies, race conditions |
| Magic numbers | Unclear intent, hard to change |
| Mutable defaults | Shared state between calls |
| Unbounded retry | Can hang indefinitely |
| Exceptions as control flow | Expected business outcomes (not found, invalid state, denied) routed through throw/catch instead of result types; forces callers to branch via catch blocks instead of switch expressions |
| Nested error handling >3 | Usually indicates business logic shoehorned into exception handlers; refactor to result types with exhaustive switch |
| Hardcoded display name maps | Single source of truth violation; breaks when backend adds new values; scattered maintenance burden |
| Unlayered data presentation | Every value shown to users needs a fallback chain; bare lookups without fallback crash on missing data |

